Pour @cold salted water{300%ml} into a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @rice{150%grams} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover, and cook for ~{10%minutes}.

Remove from the heat.

Keep covered for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to
cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, clean the @mushrooms{150%grams} with #kitchen paper{} and roughly
chop.

Remove the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve
lengthways, then thinly slice widthways.

Place a #large pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

When hot, fry the mushrooms and leek, stirring occasionally, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Remove from the pan and set
aside.

Give the pan a quick wipe then return to medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil
(if necessary).

Once the pan is hot, add the @diced Irish chicken breast{260%grams}.

Season with salt and pepper.

Fry until golden brown and cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its
> packaging. Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal
> due to packaging we use to keep it fresh.

Add the mushrooms, leek, @dried oregano{1%sachet}, @chicken stock{1%sachet}
and @creme fraiche{110%grams} to the pan.

Cook, stirring until the sauce has reduced slightly, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir through the @mustard{1%sachet} and @Worcester sauce{1%sachet}.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if you feel the sauce is too thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and divide between plates.

Place the chicken and creamy mushroom sauce on top.